@R bekenstein_bound_ceiling
  formula: I_max = 2*pi*R*E / (hbar*c*ln2)
  constants: hbar=1.0545718e-34 J*s, c=2.998e8 m/s, ln2=0.6931
  scenario_A_file_rest_energy:
    R: 1e-2 m (1 cm SSD-page region)
    m: N_bytes * m_proton = 1904709 * 1.6726e-27 kg ~ 3.19e-21 kg
    E: m*c^2 ~ 2.87e-04 J
    I_max: 8.21e+20 bits
  scenario_B_container_realistic:
    R: 1e-2 m, m: 1e-3 kg (1g SSD chiplet), E ~ 8.99e+13 J
    I_max: 2.58e+38 bits
  actual_shannon_content: 1.167e+07 bits
  headroom_container_vs_actual: 2.21e+31 x
  verdict: Bekenstein bound is NON-BINDING by ~31 orders of magnitude.
           No conceivable absorb-cycle history reaches this ceiling within the
           thermodynamic lifetime of the substrate.

@R landauer_per_absorb_floor
  formula: E_min = N_bits_flipped * kB*T*ln2
  constants: kB=1.381e-23 J/K, T=300 K, kT*ln2=2.871e-21 J/bit
  per_absorb_estimate:
    typical_shard: ~5000 lines * 60 chars * 8 bits = 2.4e+06 bits
    E_landauer_floor: 6.89e-15 J  (femtojoule scale)
  comparison_to_actual:
    SSD_write_energy_per_byte: ~1e-9 J (NVMe typical)
    actual_full_rewrite_energy: ~1.9e-03 J (millijoule scale)
    Landauer/Actual ratio: 3.6e-12 (Landauer is ~10^11 x below actual)
  verdict: Landauer bound is NON-BINDING. Energy cost is dominated by
           charge-pump / fsync / page-write overhead ~10^11 x above the
           thermodynamic floor. Energy is NOT the limiting axis.

@R compute_saturation_runtime
  empirical_absorb_runtime_s: 3.5 (midpoint of 2-5s observed)
  cron_interval_s: 300
  current_duty_cycle: 1.17%
  decomposition:
    chflags_unlock_relock: O(1) ~10ms total (3 ops)
    cat_shard_to_atlas: O(shard_size) ~50us at 500MB/s NVMe for 25KB shard
    hexa_interpreter_overhead: O(1) startup ~1-3s (DOMINANT)
    lock_state_machine: O(1) ~100ms
  scaling_law:
    absorb_runtime ~ constant + epsilon*shard_size  (atlas_size NOT in the leading term)
    atlas_size enters ONLY via downstream consumers (atlas_health, raw_audit, drill_scanner)
  consumer_tool_O(N)_saturation:
    cold_read_throughput: ~52ms per MB
    cron-budget exhaustion at: ~5755 MB atlas size (when full-read tools alone exceed 5min)
    headroom_from_current: 3061x
    cycles_to_saturation @ 25KB/shard avg: ~230128 absorb cycles
    @ current rate ~3 absorbs/day: ~210 years
  verdict: Compute-saturation ceiling is ASTRONOMICALLY distant.
           At present growth rate, atlas reaches cron-intractable size centuries after substrate failure.

@R io_bandwidth_estimate
  measured_inpage_throughput: 2039 MB/s (write to /tmp from RAM-cached source)
  realistic_NVMe_sustained: ~500 MB/s
  per_absorb_io_demand: ~25 KB shard append + ~1.88 MB locked-file revalidation
  io_floor_per_absorb: ~50 microseconds
  actual_absorb_to_io_floor_ratio: 70000x (process overhead dominates I/O by 5 orders)
  verdict: I/O bandwidth is NON-BINDING. The disk could service ~10000 absorbs/sec
           if process startup were free. I/O is NOT the limiting axis.

@R binding_physical_limit_identified
  ranked_candidates:
    [1] Bekenstein:        non-binding (31 orders headroom)
    [2] Landauer:          non-binding (11 orders below actual write cost)
    [3] I/O bandwidth:     non-binding (5 orders below process overhead)
    [4] O(N)_consumer_tools: future-binding at ~5.7 GB atlas (~210 years away)
    [5] process_overhead:   CURRENT-binding (hexa interpreter + fsync + lock state machine)
  THE_BINDING_PHYSICAL_LIMIT: process_overhead
    nature: per-cycle constant cost ~2-5s independent of atlas/shard size
    composed_of: hexa interpreter cold-start, chflags syscalls, fsync barriers, lock acquire
    why_it_binds: even with 0-byte shards, this floor remains; it sets the minimum cron interval
    saturation_threshold: when absorb_runtime > cron_interval (currently 1.17% utilization)
    headroom_to_cron_saturation: ~85x reduction in cron interval, OR ~85x growth in process cost
  edge_of_chaos_per_raw_121:
    current_regime: deeply sub-critical (1.17% duty cycle, 10^31 Bekenstein headroom)
    omega-saturation per raw 37: NOT physically threatened on any near-term timescale
    ordinal-theoretic ceiling per raw 72: orthogonal axis (formal, not physical) - DEFERRED to separate witness
  energy_landscape_per_raw_116:
    no metastable wells in physical-resource state-space
    monotone growth ~25KB/shard well below all ceilings

@R raw 91 C3 honest disclosure
  honest_caveats:
    [1] Bekenstein scenario_A uses proton-mass-per-byte as a worst-case rest-energy proxy.
        Actual file mass-equivalent (charge state energy in NAND cells) is ~10^15 x smaller.
        This makes the bound even less binding, not more.
    [2] Landauer assumes pure-flip cost; actual NAND program-erase cycles dissipate ~10^11x more.
        The "real" energy floor is the SSD controller's charge-pump efficiency, not kT*ln2.
    [3] Empirical absorb runtime (2-5s) was reported in CONTEXT, not re-measured this session
        (would require unlock-relock cycle which the task forbids - read-only).
        Confidence: medium. Cited as user-supplied empirical reference.
    [4] Consumer-tool O(N) saturation assumed cold-cache 52ms/MB; warm-cache is 10-100x faster.
        Real saturation deferred until a tool actually demonstrates O(N^2) behavior.
    [5] Process overhead identified as binding by elimination; not directly profiled this session.
        Confidence: high (consistent with reported 2-5s vs <1ms I/O).
    [6] This shard is APPEND-ONLY ledger candidate. NOT yet absorbed into atlas.n6.
        Awaits ledger-keeper unlock-append-relock cycle per raw 77.
    [7] Tri-axis per raw 72: PHYSICAL axis only. Formal (Goedel/ordinal) and computational
        (halting/complexity) ceilings explicitly deferred to companion witnesses.
    [8] No source modifications performed. Pure read-only metadata + entropy compute + write-bench.
  uncertainty_band:
    Bekenstein: ±2 orders (R and m_eff are order-of-magnitude estimates) - irrelevant to non-binding verdict
    Landauer: ±0.3 orders (constants exact, T=300K nominal) - irrelevant to non-binding verdict
    Compute-saturation: ±1 order (depends on tool implementations not benchmarked) - main uncertainty
    Binding-limit identification: high confidence given the elimination cascade

